The [[Heisman Trophy]], one of the highest individual awards in American [[college football]], has been awarded annually since its creation in 1935. The trophy is given to the most outstanding college football player in the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association]] (NCAA) [[NCAA Division I Football Bowl Subdivision|Division I Football Bowl Subdivision]] (FBS), and is awarded by the Heisman Trust, successors of the awards from the [[Downtown Athletic Club]] at an annual ceremony.

==History==
The DAC Trophy was established in 1935 by the Downtown Athletic Club in New York City to recognize the best college football player "east of the [[Mississippi River]]".<ref name="Lighten"/> In that inaugural year, the award went to [[Jay Berwanger]] from the [[Chicago Maroons football|University of Chicago]]. Berwanger was later [[NFL draft|drafted]] by the [[Philadelphia Eagles]] of the [[National Football League]] but declined to sign with them. He never played professional football for any team, instead choosing to pursue a career in business.<ref>[http://www-news.uchicago.edu/releases/02/020627.berwanger.shtml Jay Berwanger, first winner of the Heisman Trophy, 1914–2002] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080511211650/http://www-news.uchicago.edu/releases/02/020627.berwanger.shtml |date=May 11, 2008 }} Julia Morse, University of Chicago News Office. Chicago, Illinois. June 27, 2002. Accessed March 7, 2008.</ref> In 1936, the club's athletic director, football pioneer [[John Heisman]], died and the trophy was renamed in his honor. [[Larry Kelley]], the second winner of the award, was the first to win it as the "Heisman Trophy".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.heisman.com/history/heisman_trophy.php |title=The Heisman Trophy |publisher=heisman.com |access-date=January 2, 2012 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120103181703/http://www.heisman.com/history/heisman_trophy.php |archive-date=January 3, 2012 }}</ref> In addition to the name change, the award also became a nationwide achievement. With the new name, players west of the Mississippi became eligible; the first player from the western United States was selected in 1938, [[TCU Horned Frogs football|TCU]] quarterback [[Davey O'Brien]].<ref name="Lighten">[http://www.encyclopedia.com/doc/1G1-15962158.html Lighten up. (Heisman Trophy)] Mark Purdy, ''The Sporting News'', encyclopedia.com. December 5, 1994. Accessed March 8, 2008. (Site defunct prior to 9/10) {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080205161035/http://www.encyclopedia.com/doc/1G1-15962158.html |date=February 5, 2008 }}</ref>

On June 10, 2010, following several years of investigation, the NCAA announced that [[USC Trojans football|USC]] running back [[Reggie Bush]], the 2005 Heisman trophy winner, received gifts from agents while still in college. The university received major sanctions,<ref name="ESPNSanctions">[https://www.espn.com/los-angeles/ncf/news/story?id=5272615 USC punished with two-year football postseason ban] . [[ESPN]], June 11, 2010.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://assets.espn.go.com/preview/100610/espn_uscpenalties.pdf |title=NCAA infraction report |access-date=September 20, 2010 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101205163308/http://assets.espn.go.com/preview/100610/espn_uscpenalties.pdf |archive-date=December 5, 2010 }}</ref> and there were reports that the Heisman Trophy Trust would strip his award.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nfl.com/news/heisman-trust-leader-denies-decision-to-revoke-bush-s-trophy-09000d5d81a536d9 |title=news: Heisman Trust leader denies decision to revoke Bush's trophy |publisher=NFL |date=September 7, 2010 |access-date=September 20, 2010 |archive-date=August 9, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200809181058/https://www.nfl.com/news/heisman-trust-leader-denies-decision-to-revoke-bush-s-trophy-09000d5d81a536d9 |url-status=live }}</ref> In September of that year, Bush voluntarily forfeited his title as the 2005 winner. The Heisman Trust decided to leave the award vacated with no new winner to be announced for the season.<ref>{{cite news|title=Reggie Bush's Heisman to stay vacated |date=September 16, 2010 |publisher=ESPN |url=https://www.espn.com/los-angeles/ncf/news/story?id=5576729 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160110131236/http://sports.espn.go.com/los-angeles/ncf/news/story?id=5576729 |archive-date=January 10, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> Eventually, on April 24, 2024, the Heisman Trust announced the reinstatement of Bush's trophy due to 2021 rule changes regarding player compensation.<ref>{{cite news |title=Reggie Bush to have Heisman Trophy returned |date=April 24, 2024 |publisher=ESPN |url=https://www.espn.com/college-football/story/_/id/40014492/reggie-bush-heisman-trophy-returned |access-date=April 24, 2024 |archive-date=April 24, 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240424131545/https://www.espn.com/college-football/story/_/id/40014492/reggie-bush-heisman-trophy-returned |url-status=live }}</ref>

A school has had a Heisman winner in back-to-back years six times ([[Yale Bulldogs football|Yale]] 1936–37, [[Army Black Knights football|Army]] 1945–46, [[Ohio State Buckeyes football|Ohio State]] 1974–75, [[USC Trojans football|USC]] 2004–05, [[Oklahoma Sooners football|Oklahoma]] 2017–18 and [[Alabama Crimson Tide football|Alabama]] 2020–21). Only one player, Ohio State's [[Archie Griffin]], has won the award twice.<ref>[http://www.heisman.com/winners/a-griffin74.php Archie Griffin] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120104142529/http://www.heisman.com/winners/a-griffin74.php |date=January 4, 2012 }} Heisman.com. Accessed December 23, 2012.</ref> Oklahoma is the only school to have two players win the award in back-to-back years playing the same position (quarterbacks [[Baker Mayfield]] followed by [[Kyler Murray]]).

Between 1936 and 2001, the award was given at an annual gala ceremony at the Downtown Athletic Club in New York City. The Downtown Athletic Club's facilities were damaged during the [[September 11, 2001 attacks]]. Due to financial difficulties stemming from the damage, the DAC declared bankruptcy in 2002, turning over its building to creditors. Following the club's bankruptcy and the loss of the original Downtown Athletic Club building,<ref>[https://www.espn.com/espn/print?id=1583486&type=story New York landmark's closing leaves Heisman homeless]  Wayne Drehs, ESPN.com. July 22, 2004. Accessed March 8, 2008.</ref> the [[Yale Club of New York City]] assumed presenting honors in 2002 and 2003.<ref>[http://www.nydailynews.com/archives/sports/9-11-forces-heisman-move-yale-club-article-1.491867 9-11 Forces Heisman to Move to Yale Club] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230627215012/https://www.nydailynews.com/archives/sports/9-11-forces-heisman-move-yale-club-article-1.491867 |date=June 27, 2023 }} Christopher Hunt, ''New York Daily News''. June 26, 2002. Accessed December 14, 2018.</ref><ref>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/sports/2003/11/07/heisman-trophy-dinner-becomes-feast-for-the-public/5e3d9ff5-c80d-4129-87aa-f3ce4e998f10/ Heisman Trophy Dinner Becomes Feast for the Public] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181215065945/https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/sports/2003/11/07/heisman-trophy-dinner-becomes-feast-for-the-public/5e3d9ff5-c80d-4129-87aa-f3ce4e998f10/ |date=December 15, 2018 }} ''The Washington Post''. November 7, 2003. Accessed December 14, 2018.</ref> The ceremony was moved to the [[New York Marriott Marquis]] in [[Times Square]] for the 2002, 2003, and 2004 presentations. Between 2005 and 2019, the event was held at [[PlayStation Theater]] in Times Square.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.nyc-architecture.com/LM/LM063.htm|title= Downtown Athletic Club|access-date= March 7, 2008|publisher= nyc-architecture.com|archive-date= February 19, 2008|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20080219021052/http://www.nyc-architecture.com/LM/LM063.htm|url-status= usurped}}</ref> The move to the PlayStation Theater allowed the Downtown Athletic Club (and ultimately, the award's successor, The Heisman Trust) to resume full control of the event (the most prominent example of which was the return of the official portraits of past winners), despite the loss of the original presentation hall.<ref>[https://www.espn.com/college-football/columns/story?columnist=maisel_ivan&id=2255303 Bush runs away with Heisman Trophy]  Ivan Maisel, ESPN.com. December 10, 2005. Accessed March 8, 2008.</ref> Shortly after the 2019 ceremony was held, the PlayStation Theater was permanently closed; as a result, the Heisman Trust began searching for a new location to conduct the trophy presentation. The 2020 ceremony would ultimately be held at the studios of ESPN in [[Bristol, Connecticut]] due to the [[COVID-19 pandemic]], with the ceremony being held on January 5, 2021.<ref>{{Cite web|date=November 14, 2020|title=Heisman Trophy to be awarded virtually Jan. 5|url=https://www.espn.com/college-football/story/_/id/30316085/heisman-trophy-awarded-virtual-ceremony-jan-5|access-date=November 16, 2020|website=ESPN.com|language=en|archive-date=November 15, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201115162906/https://www.espn.com/college-football/story/_/id/30316085/heisman-trophy-awarded-virtual-ceremony-jan-5|url-status=live}}</ref>

In terms of balloting, the fifty states of the U.S. are split into six regions (Far West, Mid-Atlantic, Midwest, Northeast, South, Southwest), and six regional representatives are selected to appoint voters in their states.<ref>[http://nbcsports.msnbc.com/id/6700005/ Expanded Heisman Trophy Voting Results] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080218100222/http://nbcsports.msnbc.com/id/6700005/ |date=February 18, 2008 }} MSNBC.com. Accessed March 8, 2008.</ref> Each region has 145 media votes, for a total of 870 votes. In addition, all previous Heisman winners may vote, and one final vote is counted through public balloting. The Heisman ballots contain a 3–2–1 point system, in which each ballot ranks the voter's top three players and awards them three points for a first-place vote, two points for a second-place vote, and one point for a third-place vote. The points are tabulated, and the player with the highest total of points across all ballots wins the Heisman Trophy.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.heisman.com/history/balloting.php |title=Heisman Trophy Balloting |access-date=January 2, 2012 |publisher=heisman.com |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120723051736/http://www.heisman.com/history/balloting.php |archive-date=July 23, 2012 }}</ref>

